I designed this to replace the metal leaf springs on my Pro-Line Ambush RC Crawler. The metal leaf springs get kinked often and are a bit too stiff for my liking. So I'm hoping this will be a much softer ride, allow the vehicle to sit a little lower, offer more articulation, and not get kinked as easily.

Let me know if you'd like to see anything else for the Pro-Line Ambush!

Update! The original file was too thin! I've updated and the new file is proline ambush leaf spring replacement v0.2.stl

Update! I think having the holes in the design compromises and complicates the print. I added a version that does not have any holes as well as a version that does not have the center hole. Print then drill out the holes as needed. The center hole is approximately 1mm and the 2 eye holes are 3mm. I haven't tested this out yet. I think that the "proline ambush leaf spring replacement NO CENTER HOLE.stl" file will likely be the best print.

description.text: This was something that I created for a 3D printing class assignment. My class was given a set of cards. In these cards were issues proposed by people living in outer space. The issue that I was solving, was a girl's sickness. She claimed that some of the food in her planet were spoiled. I was to create a currently no-existent device that could assure others that their food was edible. The device i created is a machine that observes a food's components, whether it is molecular or microscopic.

Hi,
I like to show my modification on my CTC what I bought 3 years ago. After a lot of modification I still was not happy with the resolution of the printer. Always problems with intrusion. My first idea was to by a new cheap chinese printer what you can get for 150,- Euro. After all mechanical modification on my printer what I did already I was scared to start again with a new one.
I decided to buy the E3d solution. First just the hot end, second the titan extruder. I know, lot of many but know I got what I'm looking for.
I used the original carriage and designed some parts for it. As you see on one picture I used thread inlays for the mount. Anyway, if you can change the design in the attached dxf file.
One other thing, as you can see the design is prepared for a inductive z-sensor and auto level. A while ago I changed my board to the one from flashforge with the atmega 2560. Unfortunately up to now I was not able to activate automatic leveling in sailfish. I installed the inductive sensor on the housing. This was a big improvement. Since then I never leveled my bed again. I think a lot of problems are the reconstruction of the mechanical z limit switch.

Finally I'm quit happy with this solution. Tweaking will be still left, of course:-)

Here a short movie in motion: https://youtu.be/2fGnYb4o8Wk

Looking through Things for the extruder cooling fan, I saw many options. I had an idea of what I wanted to do, so I started with a couple of objects I found here. Something with a hinge would give me ready access but nothing suited me. So, I imported some stuff into SketchUp and started working on it.

I had already cut the heat sink, leaving the bottom five ribs mounted to the extruder frame. This took care of helping keep the heat away from the filament but I knew I should have more air flow. I checked the heat load routinely with a laser thermometer and it wasn't too bad. But, I still wanted to get the fan back in operation.

I went through about six iterations of this design before getting something I like. The bottom portion of the fan mount allows cooling air to reach the heat sink. The brace across the width of the mount lets it sit on the heat sink for stability. The upper area allows for plenty of air flow over the filament and gear assembly, letting the warm air escape from the top.

My first full 3D printable led clock case. I am still working on it, just wanted to share the idea, since I discovered alot of things and ideas made by other users.
I am still test printing it to verify if everything prints fine and fits together.

The back plane (top) will contain the led strips (60 leds/m), 5 rows with 6 leds each, and each cell will be lighted up according to the time to display.

The hardware, in my case a ESP8266, will stay outside the case to have the clock more modular since it can then be controlled by different kinds of ESP8266 modules or Arduinos.

Update 2017-04-03:
My proof of concept. :-)
Printed a first version to verify printing quality and led control. The green filament is not the best for coloring the time to display, using just white for this version. My daugther loves green!
The case does not snap together as expected, due to the solder points (I am not really good on soldering), need to adapt the required space at the outter border where the led strips ends.
The screew holes are not tight enough, need to make them little bit smaller than 3mm diameter.

Update 2017-04-14:
Finally I found the time to update the models and print a new version.
White is much better for what I was aiming for.
The stl files with suffix "v2" do have optimized holes for the screws and the main case does have more space on the outter border for solder (blubs) in case someone is also not that talented as I am in soldering.
The clock now shows hours (red), minutes (green) and seconds (blue) as also AM/PM in a different color. The colors for the AM/PM might change as soon as I did some more testing.
Printing was done in 2h53m for the top/cover, and 11h53m for the body part.
The body part I prepared in simplyfy3d like 0.2mm layer height for the first 2mm (front part), 0.1mm layer height for the numbers (about 3,2mm thickness) and 0.3mm layer for the rest of the case. My nozzle is a 0.4mm.
Next steps will be the elecrtonic part and a case for it. Stay tuned! :-)

More will follow as soon as I get there. :-)

Some years ago I started getting trouble with pain during running - I found out after some checks with doctors and orthopedics that this was because of overpronation - especially an issue with my left foot.

So after spending serious amounts of bucks I got some special soles made by my orthopedic - and this helped a lot. But these soles get worn out too, so thats why I came up with the idea to make it myself. The key here is flexibility - these are made with NinjaFlex material.

The attached STLs are made with 4% pronation degree - you can tweak this for your own needs by making your own fork of the original Onshape design. You can find it on my blog here: http://diygarageprojects.blogspot.no/2017/03/3d-printing-overpronation-insoles.html

My original soles costed me about 300USD in total. These costed me 1-2 USD....it may not be perfect still but I love the idea of making this stuff at home.

Happy making folks!

title: Corner Bracket glass plate Wanhao i3 Plus

description.text:
Update on 4/10/2017: Use the new Corner_Bracket_v2.3.stl file. From much testing and use of my iterations on this bracket, I have found that additional strengthening was needed to prevent the bolts from bending the bracket outward when tightening up against the glass plate. This version has a thicker cross bar and the corners where the bolts are placed now continue down to fully meet the crossbar. I also moved the hole for the M3 bolt to better align with the heat bed (no more carving with a X-Acto knife). I also lowered the height of the retainer clips (holding the glass) as they were interfering with the homing of the extruder tip.This version has all the changes made to date.

This remix adapts the design for a Wanhao i3 from Webberen
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1585718

This one is specifically for a Wanhao i3 Plus (may also work on a Monoprice Maker Select Plus). I found that my built/heat plate and borosilicate glass were both thicker than allowed for in his design. I also had to move the mounting hole for the M3 bolt to match that for a i3 Plus build plate. I made the clips to hold the glass a little longer as I did not have M3 bolts longer that 18mm.

description.text:
While this was designed to be accessible for the blind/low vision, it has benefits for the able-bodied as well. The tactile differences mean that it can be played in the dark and could be a great way to pass a power outage. The magnets keep the pieces where they're supposed to be despite kids, pets, earthquakes, car rides, clumsiness, etc.

Print in PLA only!

Glue 4 pcs TopCorner.stl together in an 8 x 8 square, making sure the raised and lowered squares alternate. Glue 4 pcs BottomOutsides.stl and 1 pcs BottomMiddle.stl together in an 8 x 8 square with 1 pcs BottomMiddle.stl in the middle and 2 pcs BottomOutsides.stl on each side, one 6 x 2 and one 2 x 6. Insert magnets into the bottom, making sure they're all oriented the same way (positive up or positive down). Glue the top and bottom together.

Glue 1 pcs Cross.stl into the top 1 pcs King.stl. Glue the cone from 1 pcs AltCross.stl into the cross from 1 pcs AltCross.stl and glue this into the top of another 1 pcs King.stl. Insert magnets into 16 pcs MajorMagnetBase.stl. Glue these to the bottoms of 2 pcs King.stl, 1 pcs Queen.stl, 1 pcs AltQueen, 2 pcs Rook.stl, 2 pcs AltRook.stl, 2 pcs Bishop.stl, 2 pcs AltBishop.stl, 2 pcs Knight, and 2 pcs AltKnight.stl. Insert magnets into 16 pcs MinorMagnetBase. Glue these to the bottoms of 8 pcs Pawn.stl, and 8 pcs AltPawn.stl.

While driving home with my boyfriend, the subject of chess came up. He puts me on the spot, asking what accommodations I think would be necessary to make a chess set accessible to the blind. I answer that there would need to be tactile differences between the colors, and something to keep the pieces from getting knocked over. Bingo! Usually it's a peg and hole system to keep the pieces from getting knocked over, but he said he wanted to try it with magnets and have a glass set. I realized I could 3d print a set, albeit not out of glass.

description.text:
A spool holder designed to fit onto the 20mm profile of 2020, 2040, 2060 and other such aluminum extrusions. The arm fits over an into the extrusion and the retention plate goes on the other side to sandwich the extrusion. Use M5 screws and nuts of the appropriate length for the extrusion you are attaching to with a minimum of 1.2 mm for 2020, 3.2 mm for 2040, and so on.

For the axle I used a piece of wood dowel I had lying around, wrapped with a bit of duct tape to get it to roughly 7.8mm diameter. I then put on some 8mm bearing which the spool rolls on. You can use what you want here as long as it is solid enough to hold your spool.

21/05/2017 Update: Added a version of the arms that doesn't require a plate and instead uses T-nuts with a M5 bolt to connect to the extrusion. Ideal when you don't have clearance on the sides of the spool holder.

31/05/2017 Update: Added a restrictor piece that can optionally be used. I glued a piece of felt to the inside curved surface. Slip this over the arms and spool as pictured to gently restrict the movement of the spool. This prevents the spool from spontaneously unwinding.

Printer:

CR-10

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

The STL are made so the objects are lying flat on the bed when printing. Print this way for best results. You will need to print two of each for a complete holder but I recommend you print them one set at a time. This way if your printer tolerances are off and your part won't fit onto your printer you can adjust and note have wasted as much plastic.

Use 4 screws and nuts to secure the parts together. It is normal for the center tooth on each part to have a little resistance as you push the part on, this is part of what makes a tight fit. It is not normal for the part not to fitting all the way down into the extrusion because the outside legs are too tight. If this is the case for you just size up 1% and try again.

Why I made yet another spool holder

I recently created the Volcano Direct Mount for the CR-10 printer (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2214530). As I've been using this I found that the original spool holder was creating issues with tension and filament extrusion when the print head would move away from it at far XY coordinates. A top mounted spool is one possible solution and I didn't like any of the ones I found so I decided to make a new one.

This spool holder is rigid yet light due to the framing. The way it clamps onto the aluminum extrusion is very solid. The top is open to make it easy place and take out the axle.

This things demonstrate how an OpenSCAD module can be used to eliminate the Elephant's Foot affect when designing and printing a 3D object. The module, which you can copy and paste to your own OpenSCAD scripts, insets the one or a few first layers such that they do not protrude the object outline.

title: Decora dual wall switch with LEDs

description.text:
This is a remix of the Decora Blank by Corona688. This is also alternate design remix of my other 8 button switches http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2136094 and http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2202434 .

This is a design for a decora style 2 button on/off rocker switch with indicator LEDs for each row of buttons. The buttons can be modified with indicator text. The indicator text in the default OpenSCAD file is for switches designed to control a lighted ceiling fan. each button has 2 lines of text :

FAN
ON OFF

and

LIGHT
ON OFF

The OpenSCAD file can be modified to create plain ON / OFF buttons, or buttons with 6 or 7 characters of text above the ON / OFF text. I have included .stl files to print all parts at once with FAN and LIGHT switches, just the ON / OFF buttons, or ON / OFF buttons for FAN and LIGHT
This is a variation of a project I have been working on for a MySensors switch controller. Other information as well as the prototype of this (prior to the 3D printed version) can be seen at:
https://forum.mysensors.org/topic/4317/us-decora-style-wall-switch/
The crossbar brace assembly for this model is used as a pivot for the rocker switches. The pivot is to prevent pressing both the on and the off buttons simultaneously. This is not a required piece for the switch to work, but it will give the switch a better feel.
The switch plate is designed to mount a 3cm x 7cm prototype or other circuit board similar to this:
https://console5.com/store/perforated-board-3cm-x-7cm.html
The circuit board is mounted using 2mm x 5mm self tapping screws. The switches used are 6mm x 6mm tactile switches with a switch height of 4.3mm to 5mm:
http://www.robotshop.com/en/sfe-mini-push-button-switch.html?gclid=CJyh2_fEq9ICFQEIaQodYO0LcA
The indicator LED holes are designed to hold any standard 3mm LED, though the hole size can be increased to fit larger LEDs if desired.

This design will fit a standard 30mm x 70mm prototyping board. This is the same style of proto board that I used when I made the first prototype versions of the switches. For the screws to hold the board to the switch plate I used 2mm x 5mm self tapping screws.

See my other switches I posted to get more information on the creation of these switches. You can also check out my blog post on my website that talks about how I created these. https://dan.bemowski.info/2017/06/11/my-start-into-open-source-hardware/

description.text:
ever ran your z-axis and heard a horrible squealing noise? it probably is the leadscrew rubbing against the acrylic. well here is a surefire way to fix that and to increase printing accuracy.

comments.text:
Mechanically, when you have two parallel rods, they both need to be perfectly straight. Any difference between them puts undue strain on the motor. That is why the threaded rod is left free to move. This freedom counters any inconsistencies and ensures your motor lasts as long as possible. All of the guidance is provided by the smooth rod. Any wobble on the Z-axis will be introduced via a loose bearing, the X-axis being misaligned or hanging too much weight on the top of the frame, that isn't 100% rigid.
By confining the top of the threaded rod, you shorten the life of your motors and at worst introduce skipping as the X-axis is moved, leading to inconsistency in Z-axis movement.

title: Gigantic Bastard CNC

description.text:
Why 'Gigantic Bastard'? It's really big, and it's the illegitimate offspring of the two most prominent printed CNC projects: the MPCNC and the Root 2 CNC. I created this mostly because I already had an oversized MPCNC and needed more rigidity. This thing is built like a tank, and is approximately a $50 upgrade if you already have a 25.4mm MPCNC.

Update 08/06/2017

This project is no longer being updated. If you are just starting a build, I recommend my latest full 4x8' plywood sheet CNC instead.

Update 4/3/2017

I have added 23.5mm and 25mm versions of the files. I have not tested these, but they should be correct. Use at your own risk.

A bit of info on the pieces:

spacer.stl

This is a rounded spacer used in place of washers to allow 5/16 bolts to be used in place of the M8 ones in the Root 2.1 carriage.

standoff_v2.stl

This is used to support the round tubes. You will need to drill a hole and use an M4 tap, then screw in an M4 screw about every 8-12 inches. This is the most important part of this mod -- if you don't user screws in the support, the CNC will flop around.

jig.stl

This is a jig to help you drill the holes for the standoffs. It works best if you tighten down the tubes, drill a hole, then slide to the next position and repeat. Remember that all the holes need to line up perfectly. If you mess up, just move over a bit and try again.

sideMount.stl

This piece mounts to the MPCNC rollers and to the gantry side pieces. The 3 holes fit 1/4" bolts.

zaxis.stl

This is a modified MPCNC Z axis that mounts to the Root 2.1 carriage.

tubemount.stl and tubemount_mirror.stl

These are the mounts for the round tubes and the belts.

side.dxf

This is the wooden panel that joins the MPCNC sliders to the Root 2.1 short axis.

title: One Handed Mini-Clapper for DSLR Shooters

description.text: I recently discovered the AWESOMENESS of shooting in RAW with my 5D Mark 2, thanks to the wonderful guys at http://www.magiclantern.fm/! While doing tests building my personal RAW post workflow, I found myself with the need to sync sound to the RAW footage. Many of my tests were handheld shots with a Tascam DR-100 on a hotshoe ball mount, so I needed a solution that I could operate with one hand. Of course I could use an App on my phone and get all my slate data in one go, but where's the fun in that? =)

Print Settings for Upper and Lower portions:
  • exterior support
  • 10% infill
  • 0.3mm layer height
  • 65 mm/s feedrate / travel
  • 225c extruder temp
  • 115c HBP temp
    • Print Settings for 5x10mm Pin:
  • no support
  • 100% infill
  • 0.3mm layer height
  • 25mm/s feedrate / travel
  • 225c extruder temp
  • 115c HBP temp
    • After printing, I bored out the pin holes on the "TOP" piece so that the 5x10mm retention pin fit snug. It's perfect if you have to tap it in lightly to install and remove. Enjoy! (Personal design note: The retention pin design saves from having to use an M3 bolt every time something needs to be fastened. Will try to use this technique as much as possible in the future! )
